bug.short_desc: Redundant page when set pageBreakAfter for data inside table detail row.

long_desc.thetext:
Description: Redundant page when set pageBreakAfter for data inside table(with group) detail row.
Steps to reproduce: 1. Insert a table with one column, add a group. 2. Select the data item in table detail row and set page-break-after to always. 3. Delete table header, footer and group footer rows. 4. Preview in Web Viewer and pdf.
Expected result: Each page for each detail data row.
Actual result: A page without detail data showed as the last page.
case in Regression_156969.java

1. Insert a grid with (2*1) 2. Insert labels to two cell in the only row. 3. Select first label and set page-break-after to always 4. Repeat step3 to the second label 5. Preview 6. Change two labels' page-break-after to auto and page-break-before to always. 7. Preview
Effects in step 5 and step 7 are not the same
fixed, remove redundant page
Now we can get the same result from HTML and PDF. Only one page exists when setting page-break-after, and two pages exist when setting page-break-before.
Verified in build 20061103

bug.short_desc: Indexer has problems with include paths starting with '~'

long_desc.thetext:
I'm using a cross-compiler installed in home directory, and include files are located at ~/LxNETES-3.2/include. If I setup the project to look for files at that subdirectory, the project compiles and links OK, but I get an indexer error that looks like:
Invalid project path: Include path not found (/home/my_user/workspace/my_program/Debug/~/cross_toolchain/include).
And then an indexer error in every related including line looking like:
C/C++ Indexer Problem: Preprocessor Inclusion not found: stdlib.h in file: /home/my_user/workspace/my_program/my_file.c on line: 1.
If, instead of setting the include path as ~/cross_toolchain/include
I set it up as /home/my_user/cross_toolchain/include
then I get no indexer errors, but then the project file is contaminated with the precise path to my home directory, and I cannot share it with coworkers.
Of course, a workaround is moving or linking the cross development directory to a shared directory, and then be careful not to trigger all sort of boring access right problems.
I insist that the correct include path is passed on to the compiler, however.
The ~ character is not a valid path character. It is the shell that expands it to the proper Unix directory, that's why it works in make. Not all shell support it either.

When a new bundle is created in the IDE, it seems to be added to any launch configuration that is available. This is especially annoying when a configuration has been carefully crafted.
Therefore I would like to have an option to "freeze" a launch configuration to avoid the annoying behavior previously described. If you are working with the launch configuration in that manner, you can deselect the checkbox below the table called "Add new workspace plug-ins to this launch configuration automatically". By deselecting this option, you would not have the problem described in your first paragraph.

bug.short_desc: Non Aggregate Function Extension

long_desc.thetext:
It is very easy to create aggregate functions using the ...data.aggregate extension point. I would like to see a separate extension point that allows for the creation of non-aggergate extensions. I realize that this can be done using standard java objects, but this creates a potential class-path issue for system administrators.
By allowing the creation of functions through extension, all that is required is plug-in installation which is a trivial issue. Also, using extension points would allow the functions to become a part of the BIRT Script Builder UI, with very little work on the part of the developer.
This is a very interesting point, and worth consideration.

A new mechanism will be introduced to make it more flexible for users to contribute custom functions on both run-time and design-time Thanks for the advice and please be noticed this could take some time
After discussion we decided to defer this feature to post 2.2.

bug.short_desc: Content assist doesn't let me add <function> tag to tld files

long_desc.thetext:
I don't know if this is a bug with WTP or with the XML editor.
I am editting a tld file, which already has a few tags defined and was used in production already, and the content assist doesn't let me add a <function> tag to it. The first few lines of the tld file are as follows:
?xml version="1.0" encoding="ISO-8859-1" ?> <taglib xmlns="http://java.sun.com/xml/ns/javaee" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://java.sun.com/xml/ns/javaee/web-jsptaglibrary_2_1.xsd" version="2.1">
<description> A tab library </description> <tlib-version>1.0</tlib-version>
However, if I copy and paste a function tag, complete with its children, from another source (e.g., http://java.sun.com/javaee/5/docs/tutorial/doc/JSPIntro7.html#wp102387), then suddenly the content assist kicks in and everything is ok.

Craig, When I tried creating a file with these contents, I didn't get any content assist if I had inferred grammar support disabled. It looks like the schema's either not processed properly (some problem with the physical location being remote and referencing other schemas?), or the file itself isn't written correctly. Can you determine which it is?

This seems to be a user error, although a completely forgiveable one. The masochists who defined the 'xsi:schemaLocation' in the XML Schema spec day that when namespace are used that it needs to be a white space separated list of pairs where the first thing in the list is the namespace and the second thing is the schema location. So instead of this...
xsi:schemaLocation="http://java.sun.com/xml/ns/javaee/web-jsptaglibrary_2_1.xsd"
... you need to write (brace yourself) this ...
xsi:schemaLocation="http://java.sun.com/xml/ns/javaee http://java.sun.com/xml/ns/javaee/web-jsptaglibrary_2_1.xsd"
It's unfortunate that the xml validator doesn't produce a warning in the case that you don't have a whitespace separated pair (since the root element does use a namespace it should be easy to deduce this error). Please open a separate bug for this issue.
Also, here's a hint to make editing namespaces and schema locations a bit easier. From the XML editor's outline view, select the root element and from the context menu choose 'Edit Namespaces...'. This will help you edit schema locations without needing to start at white space separated ugliness.
I'm going to resolve this as WORKSFORME. Please feel free to reopen if I've misunderstood your problem.

bug.short_desc: [DeleteFromSupport] Canonical-like connection delete behavior when installed CanonicalEditPolicy is not enabled

long_desc.thetext:
Canonical-like connection delete behavior when installed CanonicalEditPolicy is not enabled
Setup: - Create a shape with a canonical shape compartment editpart that supports enabling/disabling the canonical behavior. - Add two inner shapes with a connection between them.
If you delete the connection when the compartment is behaving canonically you expect the connection element to be deleted as well.
If you delete the connection when the compartment is not behaving canonically you do not expect the connection element to be deleted. This is not happening -- the connection element is being deleted as well.
If the compartment supports changing the canonical style, then the CanonicalEditPolicy becomes disabled. See CanonicalEditPolicy.isEnabled(). However, GraphicalEditPart.isCanonical() only calls isActive() on the CanonicalEditPolicy and not isEnabled().

bug.short_desc: [Layout] Need easy way re-route connections without moving shapes

long_desc.thetext:
A client would like to be able to re-route or remove bendpoints from multiple connections in one user gesture.
Consider this scenario: - User does an arrange all on their diagram. - This introduces bendpoints on connections to route around shapes. - The user decides he doesn't like the location of shape and moves it. RESULT: The connections to this shape are no longer routed in the best possible way. There may be extra bendpoints when they are not necessary or the connections may travel across other shapes.
Ideally, we would have some sort of "arrange connections" or "reroute connections" so that only the connections could be arranged, but the shapes could be left alone where they are. Alternatively, we could have a way for the user to be able to easily remove all the bendpoints for multiply selected connections, so this makes the task of reorganizing the connections a little eaiser.

bug.short_desc: How to retrieve Platform location as URI

long_desc.thetext: Since Platform.getLocation() is known to return a local file system path, you can use URIUtil.toURI(Platform.getLocation()). Or, use IWorkspaceRoot.getLocationURI(). URIUtil#equals should be used when comparing URIs. You can also use IFileStore#isParentOf for containment checks on URIs (obtain IFileStore from URI using EFS#getStore(URI)).
Ok to close?
yeah, sorry for late response. In some ways Platform.getLocationURI() seems nicer to me than IWorkspaceRoot.getLocationURI() but I can get the job done with what's there.

I would love to add Platform.getLocationURI(), but the problem is java.net.URI is specific to JDK 1.4, and the runtime plugin must run on foundation class libraries. The recommended generic version of Platform.getLocation() is Platform.getInstanceLocation(), from which you can obtain a URL. However, not all URIs can be expressed as URLs. It's not worth the trouble trying to be generic here because the assumption that the platform resides on the local file system is deeply embedded in most of the SDK. It is safe to assume that URIUtil.toURI(Platform.getLocation()) will give you what you need here.
